Continual Release of Differentially Private Synthetic Data

Mark Bun Boston University Marco Gaboardi Boston University Marcel Neunhoeffer Boston University Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich Wanrong Zhang Harvard University
Abstract

Motivated by privacy concerns in long-term longitudinal studies in medical and social science research, we study the problem of continually releasing differentially private synthetic data. We introduce a model where, in every time step, each individual reports a new data element, and the goal of the synthesizer is to incrementally update a synthetic dataset to capture a rich class of statistical properties. We give continual synthetic data generation algorithms that preserve two basic types of queries: fixed time window queries and cumulative time queries. We show nearly tight upper bounds on the error rates of these algorithms and demonstrate their empirical performance on realistically sized datasets from the U.S. Census Bureauâ€™s Survey of Income and Program Participation.

1 Introduction

In a longitudinal study, research subjects are repeatedly observed over an extended period of time. Longitudinal studies are essential in medicine and public health, where they are used to establish risk factors for disease (indeed, the term â€œrisk factorâ€ itself comes from the influential Framingham Heart StudyÂ [KRK+61]); in developmental psychology to track physical, social, and emotional development through childhood and aging; and in economics to understand employment and income levels and their relation to education, family, and significant life events. Longitudinal designs can be advantageous over single-shot designs in that they provide insight into group and individual-level changes over time. This aspect of the British Doctorsâ€™ survey led to the first conclusive evidence of the link between smoking and lung cancerÂ [DH56].

Nevertheless, longitudinal studies come with several important practical challenges, as well as complexity in devising sound statistical methodology. The challenge we address in this work is maintaining the privacy of research subjects. Specifically, we wish to understand when we can analyze data collected from a longitudinal study under the guarantees of differential privacyÂ [DMNS06]. While most algorithmic research in differential privacy focuses on single-shot data analysis, alternative models are well-equipped to address privacy in longitudinal collections. For instance, in the continual observation model of Dwork, Naor, Pitassi, and RothblumÂ [DNPR10] and Chan, Shi, and SongÂ [CSS11], individual data is presented to an algorithm in a streaming fashion, and the goal of the algorithm is to produce an estimate of one or more summary statistics of the data at every time step. â€œUser-levelâ€ differential privacy in this model guarantees that this algorithmâ€™s entire sequence of outputs is insensitive to changing any individualâ€™s contribution, even if that individualâ€™s data appears arbitrarily many times in the stream. Various problems have been studied in the continual observation modelÂ [MMNW11, JKT12, BFM+13, KPXP14, CMHM17, SLM+18, JRSS21, CR22, ABC22, EMM+23], primarily motivated by networking and internet monitoring applications with extremely long time horizons.

Meanwhile, longitudinal data analysis for health and social science research has several features not fully captured in existing work. These include:

Synthetic data.

Analysts of privacy-protected datasets often want access in the form of synthetic data (a.k.a. synthesized microdata), which are sets of individual records whose statistical properties are similar to those of the original dataset. Synthetic data is a requirement for some releases, e.g., the 2020 Census of Population and Housing tabulations. In general, synthetic data facilitates exploratory data analysis and the use of existing analysis pipelines.

Structured updates.

In each reporting period of a longitudinal study, each individual is asked the same set of questions, and an update only needs to be produced after all of the data for that period has been reported. In contrast, prior work (e.g.,Â [GRST22]) considered individual data contributions that could be interleaved in an arbitrary order, and required updates after every contribution. The additional structure of longitudinal collections may be used to design more efficient algorithms.

Small samples.

Longitudinal studies are complex to plan and expensive to run, often resulting in relatively small sample sizes. This makes it especially important for differentially private solutions to exhibit reasonable accuracy for realistic dataset sizes and parameter settings.

To capture these goals, we propose the following specialization of the continual observation model to enable the continual release of differentially private synthetic data. A non-baseline.

A first attempt at continually generating private synthetic data might be to try recomputing a new synthetic dataset from scratch in every round. In each time step tğ‘¡t, one could apply a single-shot synthetic data generator to the portion of the dataset observed up to time tğ‘¡t that yields accurate answers with respect to ğ’¬tsubscriptğ’¬ğ‘¡\mathcal{Q}_{t}. Composition theorems for differential privacy show that the worst-case error incurred overall is roughly Tğ‘‡\sqrt{T} times larger than the single-shot generatorâ€™s. Besides this automatic hit to accuracy, this algorithm has the weakness that the synthetic dataset produced at time t+1ğ‘¡1t+1 may consist of entirely different records than that at time tğ‘¡t. This can create inconsistency between analyses conducted on the synthetic data after each of these time steps. In contrast, our problem specification requires synthetic individuals to persist over time and for the longitudinal synthetic data generator to update their records incrementally. This is challenging, as even at time step t=1ğ‘¡1t=1, the synthetic data generator must prepare synthetic records (x^1t,â€¦,x^mt)superscriptsubscript^ğ‘¥1ğ‘¡â€¦superscriptsubscript^ğ‘¥ğ‘šğ‘¡(\hat{x}_{1}^{t},\dots,\hat{x}_{m}^{t}) in anticipation of all future queries and arbitrary future data records, as it cannot go back and change these values once they are released. Our consistency requirement is not only natural from the standpoint of using the synthetic data but as we shall see below, this way of thinking about the problem helps us design algorithms whose accuracy does not need to incur a polyâ¡(T)polyğ‘‡\operatorname{poly}(T) overhead over the single-shot case.

Our results.

We study the continual private synthetic data generation problem for two fundamental classes of queries. We give theoretical error guarantees (essentially matched by lower bounds) and experimental evidence suggesting that they permit reasonable accuracy for social science datasets. A motivating case study for both the theoretical models and experiments in this paper is the US Census Bureauâ€™s Survey of Income and Program Participation (SIPP)Â [Bur21]. The SIPP conducts monthly interviews of individuals to track income, employment, family composition, and participation in food and unemployment assistance programs. The problem of generating synthetic data for SIPP was previously considered inÂ [BSA13, BCE18], but without the formal protections of differential privacy.

Our algorithms for both problems follow a natural two-stage approach. Another issue in synthetic data generation is the possibility that noisy histogram bin counts may go negative.

NaÃ¯vely clamping counts to be nonnegative does not work, as we cannot resurrect nonzero counts from zero counts at subsequent time steps. We overcome this issue by padding the initial synthetic dataset so that every histogram bin is well-represented. With high probability over the entire run of the algorithm, no noisy counts will ever go negative to cancel out the padding completely. Note that while the padding introduces bias into the estimates of each histogram bin, the amount of this bias is public information and can be corrected in additional post-processing if the analyst chooses to do so. The first condition corresponds to the fact that (synthetic) individualsâ€™ Hamming weights can only increase over time. The second corresponds to the fact that Hamming weights can only increase by at most 111 each time step. Neither condition is automatically guaranteed by the tree-based aggregation mechanism but can be ensured by an additional monotonization procedure that adapts a technique fromÂ [CSS11] for ensuring the monotonicity condition (1).

1.1 Related work

While, to our knowledge, the problem of differentially private longitudinal synthetic data generation has yet to be studied, solutions to related questions have previously appeared in the differential privacy literature. Motivated by the problem of counting distinct elements in data streams, Ghazi, Kumar, Manurangsi, and NelsonÂ [GKMN22] studied variants of our cumulative time queries problem. In their terminology, our cumulative time queries problem corresponds to answering CountOccâ‰¥bsuperscriptCountOccabsentğ‘\mathrm{CountOcc}^{\geq b} queries, for all bğ‘b simultaneously, in their cumulative, item-level DP, bundle setting. Our solution also immediately implies an O~â€‹(T/n)~ğ‘‚ğ‘‡ğ‘›\tilde{O}(\sqrt{T}/n)-error algorithm for answering CountOcc=bsuperscriptCountOccabsentğ‘\mathrm{CountOcc}^{=b} queries for all bğ‘b simultaneously in their time window, item-level DP, bundle setting that follows from the fact that the number of individuals producing bit 111 exactly bğ‘b times between time steps t1<t2subscriptğ‘¡1subscriptğ‘¡2t_{1}<t_{2} can be expressed as the difference between the number of individuals with Hamming weight at least bğ‘b up to time t2subscriptğ‘¡2t_{2} and the number of individuals with Hamming weight at least bâˆ’1ğ‘1b-1 up to time t1subscriptğ‘¡1t_{1}. Using similar constructions to ours (and also building on a prior reduction ofÂ [BFM+13]), [GKMN22] studied these and related problems when the goal is to answer queries for any fixed single value of bğ‘b. Our algorithm simultaneously permits accurate estimation of these queries for all bğ‘b while also incrementally generating synthetic data matching these query answers.

Complementing work in the central model, there has also been extensive work on longitudinal data release under the stronger constraint of local differential privacy. Googleâ€™s RAPPOR systemÂ [EPK14] enables tracking the population-level average of a single Boolean statistic (corresponding to our fixed time windows problem with k=1ğ‘˜1k=1) under a heuristic assumption that each individualâ€™s bit flips its value only a small number of times. These ideas were developed further by [EFM+19], who gave an algorithm with error that scales with an upper bound on the number of times any individualâ€™s bit can flip its value rather than the overall time horizon. And while it is not posed as a synthetic data generation problem, the task of incrementally generating synthetic data from their noisy estimates is immediate when k=1ğ‘˜1k=1. [JRUW18] studied a similar problem, but in a model where it is further assumed that individuals come from distinct subpopulations, and in each time step, each individual independently draws a fresh bit from their subpopulation-specific distribution. Additional work on continual frequency estimation in the local model includesÂ [DKY17, OWW22, XYH+22, APPG22].

For simplicity, we implement our algorithm for synthetic data release with respect to cumulative time queries using the classic binary tree counter. But it could be implemented using an arbitrary differentially private algorithm for tracking the sum of a stream of bits. Our formal description of AlgorithmÂ 3 is indeed stated in terms of a generic stream counter algorithm. Stream counters enjoying improved concrete accuracy guarantees have been the focus of recent attentionÂ [Hon15, DMR+22, FHU22, HUU23], and using them in place of the tree counter in our work may yield improved experimental results.

1.2 Limitations

Synthetic data can enable analysts to answer supported queries without prior knowledge and without modifying their analysis pipelines. This is the main reason behind the demand for tabular synthetic data and why it is a legal requirement for certain data releases. Nevertheless, it is understood to be intrinsically less accurate or efficient to generate compared to noisy query answers. It is important to acknowledge that synthetic data may not always match the accuracy of DP query answers that can be released through some other data structureÂ [AACM+21].

Synthetic data is also intrinsically limited in the scope of analyses it permits. Our work identifies restricted but expressive classes of queries that permit accurate synthetic data generation algorithms. This approach aligns with the existing literature on DP single-shot synthetic data release, which provides theoretical accuracy guarantees for specific query classes. We envision restricted synthetic data as just part of a larger privacy-preserving data access system, where after performing initial exploratory data analysis on synthetic data, analysts may then decide to go through additional approvals to access the original data or to more accurate estimates.

Note also that even in the single-shot case, releasing synthetic data that preserves answers to specific queries can be computationally hard. For instance, preserving answers to 2-way marginal queries, a seemingly mild extension of the fixed time window queries considered in this paper, for k=2ğ‘˜2k=2,222Specifically, the class of 2-way marginals consists of all queries of the form qi,jâ€‹(x1,â€¦,xT)=xiâˆ§xjsubscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘—superscriptğ‘¥1â€¦superscriptğ‘¥ğ‘‡superscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–superscriptğ‘¥ğ‘—q_{i,j}(x^{1},\dots,x^{T})=x^{i}\land x^{j}. Fixed time window queries for k=2ğ‘˜2k=2 enable answering all such queries that take the form qi,i+1subscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘–1q_{i,i+1}. is computationally intractableÂ [UV11] for worst-case data, under standard cryptographic assumptions.

3 Generating Synthetic Data for Fixed Time Window Queries

In this section, we consider fixed time window queries. The goal is to produce differentially private synthetic data such that the histogram of the synthetic data approximates the corresponding histogram on the original dataset for every time window of width kğ‘˜k.

3.1 Algorithm

Our algorithm consists of two phases at each step. The first phase is to compute the noisy private statistics about the data in the most recent length-kğ‘˜k window. 5 Experiments

In this section, we study the empirical performance of the algorithms introduced in this paper. We show how the algorithms perform with a real data application and apply our algorithms to data from the Survey of Income and Program Participation (SIPP) by the U.S. Census BureauÂ [Bur21]. Unless otherwise stated, we use noise-adding mechanisms with the variance Ïƒ2superscriptğœ2\sigma^{2} calibrated to achieve overall 0.0050.0050.005-zCDP. Code to replicate the experiments is part of the Supporting Information of this paper.

Simulated Data.

First, we evaluate Algorithm 1 on rather extreme simulated data. We set the number of observations nğ‘›n to 250002500025000 and the time horizon Tğ‘‡T to 121212. We choose these values to demonstrate typical data sizes in longitudinal studies (e.g., 250002500025000 survey respondents with monthly measurements for one year). In the extreme setting, all data updates are set to 111. We then generate synthetic data to preserve fixed-time window queries using a window size kğ‘˜k of 333 (e.g., to reflect an interest in quarterly statistics).

Figure 1 summarizes the results of 100010001000 repeated runs of Algorithm 1. In the top panel of Figure 1, we show the (desired) scenario where the fixed window size kğ‘˜k specified to the synthesizer coincides with the window size of the query we are evaluating. As predicted by Theorem 3.2, the empirical error remains constant across time. In the middle panel, we highlight an advantage of releasing synthetic and padding data. Since all fixed time window queries with a window size at most kğ‘˜k of the synthesizer can be written as a low-weight linear combination of width-kğ‘˜k queries, the synthesized data remains accurate for these queries as well. Finally, we display what happens if the window size of the query exceeds kğ‘˜k of the synthesizer. Given our algorithm, we do not expect the synthetic data to preserve queries of longer window sizes. Indeed, we can observe that the empirical error increases substantially. We suggest that this warrants a word of caution for synthetic data analysts: Only queries supported by the synthesizer can be answered accurately. We cannot expect reasonable accuracy guarantees for queries not specifically supported by the synthesizer.

In Figure 2, we show that the debiasing step is essential. Calculating the proportions on the synthetic data directly leads to a substantially larger error.

Real Data Application: Releasing Poverty Rates from the Survey of Income and Program Participation (SIPP).

We now turn to an application of Algorithm 1 to data collected in the SIPPÂ [Bur21]. We downloaded the 2021 sample from https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/sipp/data/datasets/2021/pu2021_csv.zip and detail the pre-processing steps in the Appendix. We aim to estimate the proportion of households in the SIPP data that are in poverty.

We need to take a couple of data pre-processing steps to get the SIPP data into shape for our data synthesizer. First, in the SIPP data, it is possible that multiple persons per household are surveyed. Thus, we first subset the data to one longitudinal series per household. The SIPP variable â€˜THINCPOVT2â€™ is coded as the household income ratio to the household poverty threshold in a given month. We binarize this such that any values of the ratio smaller than one are coded as 111 (indicating that a household was in poverty in a given month). Finally, some households have missing values. We delete every household that has at least one missing value. Our final SIPP data sample consists of 233742337423374 households (N=23374ğ‘23374N=23374) with 121212 monthly measurements (T=12ğ‘‡12T=12) for 2021 that indicate whether a household was in poverty in a given month. For our experiment, we treat this SIPP sample as ground truth. This means our goal is to accurately estimate the proportion of households in poverty in the SIPP sample. This differs from making inferences about a larger population (from which the sample was drawn). We leave it to future work to integrate DP longitudinal synthetic data with inferential statistics and to compare the magnitude of sampling noise to the magnitude of the privacy noise. Furthermore, we focus on one particular poverty indicator, â€œHousehold income-to-poverty ratio in this month, including Type 2 individualsâ€.

Synthetic data for fixed time window queries.

We then synthesize the SIPP sample with a fixed window size of 3 (k=3ğ‘˜3k=3) to reflect quarterly measurements and repeat the synthesizer 100010001000 times. We present the results in Panel of Figures 4-5 for different values of the privacy parameter ÏğœŒ\rho. To estimate the proportion of households in poverty in a given quarter, it is natural to examine four different quantities. First, the proportion of households in poverty for at least one month of the quarter. Second, is the proportion of households in poverty for at least two months of the quarter. Third, the proportion of households in poverty for at least two consecutive months of the quarter. And fourth, the proportion of households in poverty for all three months of the quarter. A major advantage of our synthetic data approach is that we can answer any such query written as a linear combination of histogram queries (with a fixed window size of at most kğ‘˜k) without any additional privacy cost. In the right panels of Figures 3-5, we show that our approach leads to unbiased estimates of the quantities (by subtracting the query answer on the padding data from the query answer on the complete synthetic data) with good accuracy. In the left panels of Figures 3-5, we show that ignoring the debiasing step can lead to substantial bias.

Synthetic data based on cumulative time queries.

Finally, we show how to release DP synthetic data from Algorithm 3. With the DP synthetic data based on cumulative time queries, we can answer queries like â€œhow many households were at least three months in poverty in any given monthâ€. In Figure 6, we show that these queries can be accurately answered using the DP synthetic data based on cumulative time queries.While Algorithm 3 generates synthetic data for all time thresholds bğ‘b from 1,â€¦,T1â€¦ğ‘‡1,\dots,T simultaneously, we here focus on the results for setting the threshold to b=3ğ‘3b=3.

In Figure 7 we show the empirical error distribution across 100010001000 repeated applications of our algorithm on the SIPP data and compare it to the worst-case error presented in Corollary 4.1.
